    {
      "id": "culture",
      "type": "culture",
      "title": {
        "fr": "Culture",
        "ty": "Te haapiira'a",
        "en": "Culture"
      },
      "content": {
        "text": {
          "fr": "L'architecture traditionnelle polynésienne privilégie les matériaux naturels comme le bambou, les feuilles de pandanus et le bois. Les maisons traditionnelles (fare) sont conçues pour la ventilation naturelle et l'adaptation au climat tropical. Le concept de 'utuafare (famille élargie) influence l'organisation de l'espace domestique, favorisant les espaces communs et l'hospitalité.",
          "ty": "Te huru fare tupuna porinētia e fa'anahonaho nei i te mau mea taiao e pehe ai te 'ofe, te mau rau fara ma te rā'au. Te mau fare tupuna e hāmani hia no te mata'i taiao ma te fa'atau'ē i te taime mahana. Te mana'o 'utuafare e fa'ahiti nei i te huru fa'aterera'a 'ōfa'i, e fa'anahonaho nei i te mau 'ōfa'i tōtahi ma te fa'amaita'i manihini.",
          "en": "Traditional Polynesian architecture favors natural materials like bamboo, pandanus leaves, and wood. Traditional houses (fare) are designed for natural ventilation and adaptation to the tropical climate. The concept of 'utuafare (extended family) influences domestic space organization, favoring common areas and hospitality."
        }
      }
    },
